properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: More early season snowfall expected on Friday as Arctic air arrives. Below seasonal temperatures to continue through the weekend. A low pressure system will pass just off Vancouver Island Friday morning and move onto the Washington coast Friday evening. Meanwhile, modified Arctic air will advance southward through the B.C. interior. By Friday afternoon, the Arctic front is expected to reach Kamloops and pile up against the east side of the Rockies. With a somewhat cool airmass already in place, widespread snow is expected from the Chilcotin and 100 MIle area to the Fraser Canyon and eastward to the Kootenays and parts of the Columbias. Snow may become mixed with rain over southern and eastern portions of this area. Currently, forecast snowfall amounts range from 5 to 15 cm. In the wake of the low, a drying trend begins on Saturday as the Arctic air spreads through the rest of the southern interior. Temperatures of 10 degrees below seasonal normals are expected through the weekend. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.
Expires: 2020-10-23T09:41:06-00:00

properties.Title: Snow Squall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow squalls are expected. Under the snow squall bands, visibilities will be significantly reduced due to the heavy snow combined with blowing snow, and snow will quickly accumulate. A cold airmass combined with winds off the waters of Lake Winnipeg will create a favourable setup for snowsqualls. Westerly winds this evening will initially place most of the snowsqualls in the Poplar River area. However, overnight the winds are expected to shift to the northwest repositioning the snowsqualls towards the Berens River area. The snowsqualls are expected to remain in this area on Friday. Snow amounts will be highly localized but may exceed 20 to 30 cm in some areas by the time the snow squalls diminish on Saturday night as the wind shifts to a more northerly direction. ### Snow squalls cause weather conditions to vary considerably; changes from clear skies to heavy snow within just a few kilometres are common. Visibility will be suddenly reduced to near zero at times in heavy snow and blowing snow. Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.
Expires: 2020-10-23T12:41:48-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2020-10-22T20:42:48-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.2503217813.2020
Area: Poplar River, Berens River, Little Grand Rapids and Atikaki Prov. Park, Bloodvein

properties.Title: Tropical Cyclone Information Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: For Hurricane Epsilon. The next information statement will be issued by 9:30 p.m. NDT Friday. Summary of basic information at 9:30 p.m. NDT. Location: Near 32.2 North 61.5 West. About 310 kilometres east of Bermuda. Maximum sustained winds: 140 kilometres per hour. Present movement: North-northwest at 15 kilometres per hour. Minimum central pressure: 968 millibars. Hurricane Epsilon will enter the Canadian Response Zone on Saturday but is not expected to have any direct impacts on Canadian land areas other than some ocean swells along the south-facing coastlines of Nova Scotia and Newfoundland. Some rain from a developing trough of low pressure well ahead of Epsilon will spread over southeastern Newfoundland Saturday evening, but the center of Epsilon will track well offshore near the southeastern corner of the Grand Banks early on Sunday bringing gale to storm force winds to extreme offshore waters. The Canadian Hurricane Centre will provide another update on Epsilon by 9:30 PM NDT Friday. Forecaster(s): Borgel ### Please continue to monitor alerts issued by the Canadian Hurricane Centre and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: More early season snowfall expected on Friday as Arctic air arrives. Below seasonal temperatures to continue through the weekend. A low pressure system will pass just off Vancouver Island Friday morning and move onto the Washington coast Friday evening. Meanwhile, modified Arctic air will advance southward through the B.C. interior. By Friday afternoon, the Arctic front is expected to reach Kamloops and pile up against the east side of the Rockies. With a somewhat cool airmass already in place, widespread snow is expected from Bella Coola and Whistler eastward to 100 Mile and the southwest interior, and further to the Kootenays and parts of the Columbias. Snow may become mixed with rain over southern and eastern portions of this area. Currently, forecast snowfall amounts range from 5 to 15 cm. In the wake of the low, a drying trend begins on Saturday as the Arctic air spreads through the rest of the southern interior. Temperatures of 10 degrees below seasonal normals are expected through the weekend. ### Weather in the mountains can change suddenly resulting in hazardous driving conditions. Road conditions are available at www.drivebc.ca. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.
